SIMPLE: doggerel
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Doggerel
<hw>Dog"ger*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>dogerel</ets>.]</ety> <def>Low in style, and irregular in measure;
<as>as, <ex>doggerel</ex> rhymes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This may well be rhyme <qex>doggerel</qex>, quod he.</q> <rj><qau>
Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Doggerel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Doggerel
<hw>Dog"ger*el</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sort of loose or irregular
verse; mean or undignified poetry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Doggerel</qex> like that of Hudibras.</q> <rj><qau>
Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ill-spelt lines of <qex>doggerel</qex> in which he expressed
his reverence for the brave sufferers.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Doggerman</ent>⟦br⟧
